Health department officials have temporarily closed a community healthcare centre in Inanda where six nurses tested positive for COVID-19. Courtesy #DStv403 DURBAN - KwaZulu-Natal Premier Sihle Zikalala says all employees at a community healthcare centre in Inanda -- north of Durban -- are waiting for their COVID-19 test results. The facility was temporarily closed after six nurses tested positive. Community members have been advised to use nearby health facilities instead. READ: KZN health clinic closed after six nurses test positive for COVID-19 "Following the positive testing of four nurses and one doctor, the department took a decision to close the facility," Zikalala said. "This was done as a safety precaution and to allow for the decontamination of the facility in accordance with the established protocol. READ:Â SA Lockdown: KZN preparing for level 3 "We've since tested all employees for COVID-19 and their results are being conveyed to them on a continuous basis." Employees who test negative will be allowed to return to work after a period of quarantine. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.